<TITLE> Flood situation improving: FFWC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 9 (bdnews24.com)  The country will be over the worst of the floods by the end of the week, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre has said. The overall flood situation will see significant signs of improvement in a couple of days, the flood forecast said on Tuesday. The situation in the northern districts continued improving on Tuesday, while the central, south-central districts saw slight changes for the better. The Brahmaputra-Jamuna waters were receding at a higher rate and the trend will continue for next three or four days. The Ganges also continued abating and was likely to continue doing so for the next couple of days. The water level in the confluence of both the rivers (the Padma at Goalundo and Bhagyakul) started receding and will continue to fall with a greater pace from Wednesday. The Meghna remained steady and was expected to start receding by 48 hours, the FFWC bulletin said. The inundation of lowlands in the eastern part of Dhaka City and outside of Dhaka City flood protection embankment is likely to start improving in the next 48 hours. Flood situation Kurigram, Bogra, Jamalpur, Sirajganj, Tangail, Munshiganj and Manikganj districts continued improving significantly. The situation also started getting better in south-central districts including Rajbari, Faridpur, Madaripur, Shariatpur, Gopalganj, Chandpur, and Dohar and Nawabganj of Dhaka district. It was expected to improve further by the end of the week, the FFWC said. b
